By modern standards, the lack of consistent ranges for the various integral types sucks (especially in a language designed to be portable).Fixed-width integersTo address the above issues, C++11 provides an alternate set of integer types that are guaranteed to be the same size on any architecture. Because the size of these integers is fixed, they are calledfixed-width integers.The fixed-width integers are defined (in the <cstdint>\ header) as follows:NameFixed SizeFixed RangeNotesstd::int8_t1 byte signed-128 to 127Treated like a signed char on many systems. See note below.std::uint8_t1 byte unsigned0 to 255Treated like an unsigned char on many systems. See note below.std::int16_t2 byte signed-32,768 to 32,767std::uint16_t2 byte unsigned0 to 65,535std::int32_t4 byte signed-2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647std::uint32_t4 byte unsigned0 to 4,294,967,295std::int64_t8 byte signed-9,223,372,036,854,775,808 to 9,223,372,036,854,775,807std::uint64_t8 byte unsigned0 to 18,446,744,073,709,551,615Here’s an example:#include <cstdint> // for fixed-width integers
#include <iostream>

int main()
{
    std::int32_t x { 32767 }; // x is always a 32-bit integer
